VALUES
(44, 18, 9, 44, 27, 23, 25, 'Be not afraid', 'Divine Assurance in Adversity', 'Both passages emphasize God''s reassurance to Paul in times of fear. In Acts 18:9, God tells Paul, ''Be not afraid,'' while in Acts 27:24, an angel reiterates, ''Fear not, Paul.''', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 9, 24, 1, 17, 17, 'be not afraid', 'Encouragement to Speak Boldly', 'Both passages emphasize the command to speak without fear. In Acts, Paul is told to ''be not afraid,'' while Jeremiah is instructed to ''be not dismayed.'' This connection highlights a shared theme of divine encouragement in the face of opposition.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 9, 33, 3, 8, 8, 'Be not afraid, but speak', 'Encouragement to Speak Boldly', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine empowerment for speaking truth. Both passages emphasize the importance of declaring God''s message without fear, as seen in Paul''s vision and Micah''s declaration of judgment.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 9, 47, 12, 1, 3, 'speak, and hold not thy peace', 'Visions and Revelations Connection', 'Both passages emphasize divine communication through visions. Acts 18:9 shows the Lord speaking to Paul, while 2 Corinthians 12:1 mentions coming to visions and revelations of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 47, 12, 9, 9, 'I am with thee', 'Divine Presence and Strength', 'This connection highlights the assurance of God''s presence and support in both passages. Acts 18:10 emphasizes God''s protection, while 2 Corinthians 12:9 speaks to the sufficiency of God''s grace and strength in weakness.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 2, 4, 12, 12, 'I am with thee', 'Divine Presence and Assurance', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s assurance of presence. Both passages emphasize that God will be with the individual, providing support and guidance in their mission.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 23, 41, 10, 10, 'I am with thee', 'Divine Presence and Assurance', 'Both passages emphasize God''s promise of presence and support. The phrase ''I am with thee'' in both verses highlights God''s assurance to His people during times of fear and uncertainty.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 40, 28, 20, 20, 'I am with thee', 'Presence of God in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the assurance of God''s presence in both passages. Acts 18:10 states, ''I am with thee,'' while Matthew 28:20 emphasizes, ''I am with you alway.''', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 43, 10, 16, 16, 'I am with thee', 'Divine Presence and Community', 'This connection highlights the assurance of divine presence in both passages. Acts 18:10 emphasizes God''s protection and presence among ''much people,'' while John 10:16 speaks of gathering ''other sheep'' into one fold, suggesting a communal aspect under divine guidance.', 'theme', 0.37, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 45, 8, 31, 31, 'for I am with thee', 'God''s Protection and Presence', 'Both passages emphasize God''s protective presence. Acts 18:10 assures that God is with Paul, while Romans 8:31 declares that if God is for us, no one can oppose us.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 10, 55, 4, 22, 22, 'I am with thee', 'Presence of the Lord', 'This connection highlights the assurance of the Lord''s presence in both passages. Acts 18:10 emphasizes God''s promise of being with Paul, while 2 Timothy 4:22 invokes the presence of the Lord Jesus Christ with Timothy''s spirit.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 11, 44, 14, 3, 3, 'teaching the word of God', 'Teaching and Boldness in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the act of teaching and speaking boldly about the word of God. Acts 18:11 mentions teaching the word of God, while Acts 14:3 highlights speaking boldly in the Lord, suggesting a shared theme of proclaiming God''s message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 11, 44, 19, 10, 10, 'teaching the word of God', 'Duration of Teaching Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the length of time spent teaching the word of God. Acts 18:11 mentions a year and six months, while Acts 19:10 states two years, highlighting a sustained effort in spreading the message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 11, 44, 20, 31, 31, NULL, 'Duration of Teaching Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the length of Paul''s teaching ministry, with Acts 18:11 noting a year and six months and Acts 20:31 referencing three years. This connection highlights Paul''s commitment to teaching and warning the believers over an extended period.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 44, 13, 7, 7, NULL, 'Deputies in Paul’s Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the role of deputies in Paul’s ministry. In Acts 13:7, Sergius Paulus, a deputy, seeks to hear the word of God, while in Acts 18:12, Gallio, another deputy, is involved in a legal matter concerning Paul.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 44, 13, 50, 50, 'made insurrection with one accord', 'Persecution Against Paul', 'Both passages emphasize the coordinated efforts of the Jews to oppose Paul. In Acts 18:12, they act ''with one accord'' to bring him to judgment, while in Acts 13:50, they stir up others to expel Paul and Barnabas.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 40, 27, 19, 19, 'judgment seat', 'Judgment Seat Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a ''judgment seat'' where significant decisions are made regarding individuals. In Acts, Paul is brought before Gallio''s judgment seat, while in Matthew, the judgment seat is where Pilate receives a warning about Jesus. This connection highlights the theme of judicial authority in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 45, 15, 26, 26, 'Achaia', 'Connection Between Achaia References', 'This connection highlights the mention of Achaia in both passages. In Acts, Achaia is the location of Paul''s trial, while in Romans, it is noted as a region contributing to the poor saints in Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 46, 16, 15, 15, 'Achaia', 'Connection between Achaia and ministry', 'This connection highlights the geographical link between Achaia, where Gallio served as deputy, and the house of Stephanas, noted for their ministry. Both passages emphasize the significance of Achaia in the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 47, 1, 1, 1, 'Achaia', 'Connection between Paul and Achaia', 'This connection highlights Paul''s ministry in Achaia, where he faced opposition from the Jews in Acts. Both passages emphasize the significance of Corinth and Achaia in Paul''s apostolic work.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 12, 47, 9, 2, 2, 'Achaia', 'Connection between Achaia and readiness', 'This connection highlights the mention of Achaia in both passages, linking Paul''s experience in Acts with the readiness of the Corinthians in 2 Corinthians. Both passages emphasize the significance of Achaia in the context of communal response and support.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 13, 44, 25, 8, 8, 'worship God contrary to the law', 'Legal Defense in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the defense of Paul against accusations of violating the law. In Acts 18:13, he is accused of persuading men contrary to the law, while in Acts 25:8, he asserts that he has not offended against the law of the Jews.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 13, 44, 6, 13, 13, 'worship God contrary to the law', 'Accusations Against Believers', 'Both passages emphasize accusations made against individuals for speaking contrary to the law. Acts 18:13 refers to persuading men to worship God contrary to the law, while Acts 6:13 mentions blasphemous words against the law.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 13, 44, 21, 28, 28, 'worship God contrary to the law', 'Accusations Against Paul', 'Both passages emphasize accusations against Paul for teaching contrary to the law. In Acts 18:13, he is accused of persuading men to worship God contrary to the law, while in Acts 21:28, he is charged with teaching against the law and bringing Greeks into the temple.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 13, 44, 24, 5, 6, 'worship God contrary to the law', 'Accusations Against Paul', 'Both passages emphasize accusations made against Paul regarding his teachings and actions. In Acts 18:13, he is accused of persuading men to worship God contrary to the law, while in Acts 24:5-6, he is labeled as a ringleader of the Nazarenes and accused of profaning the temple.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 13, 44, 18, 4, 4, 'persuadeth men to worship God', 'Persuasion in Worship Context', 'Both passages emphasize the act of persuading men regarding worship. In Acts 18:4, the focus is on reasoning in the synagogue, while Acts 18:13 highlights the accusation of persuading contrary to the law.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 13, 44, 18, 15, 15, 'worship God contrary to the law', 'Legal Disputes in Worship', 'This connection highlights the legal implications of worship practices. Both passages emphasize the distinction between religious beliefs and civil law, suggesting that the matter at hand is not a legal issue for the judge.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 14, 60, 3, 14, 15, NULL, 'Suffering for Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering for righteousness, as both passages address the response to unjust accusations. Acts 18:14 presents a scenario where Paul is defended against false charges, while 1 Peter 3:14 encourages believers to remain steadfast when facing persecution for their faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 14, 41, 9, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Suffering and Patience', 'This connection highlights the theme of enduring patience in the face of challenges. Both passages reflect a sense of suffering and the expectation of faithfulness from others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 14, 42, 21, 12, 15, NULL, 'Persecution and Divine Wisdom', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of being brought before rulers and the assurance of divine wisdom in response. In Acts, Gallio''s statement reflects a judicial context where Paul is defended, while Luke promises that believers will receive wisdom when facing persecution. This connection highlights the theme of divine support during trials.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 14, 44, 13, 18, 18, NULL, 'Endurance in Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of enduring difficult circumstances. In Acts 18:14, Gallio''s response reflects a tolerance for the Jews'' grievances, paralleling how God ''suffered'' the Israelites'' behaviors in Acts 13:18 during their trials in the wilderness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 14, 45, 13, 3, 3, 'matter of wrong or wicked lewdness', 'Authority and Justice in Governance', 'This connection highlights the role of rulers in maintaining justice. Both passages emphasize that rulers should support good works and address wrongdoing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 14, 47, 11, 1, 1, 'bear with you', 'Connection of Endurance in Folly', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of enduring folly. In Acts, Gallio suggests that he would bear with the Jews if their matter were serious, while in 2 Corinthians, Paul asks the Corinthians to bear with him in his folly.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 15, 44, 23, 29, 29, NULL, 'Legal Questions in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize accusations related to ''law.'' In Acts 18:15, the speaker declines to judge matters of law, while Acts 23:29 notes the accused faced questions of their law without charges worthy of punishment.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 15, 44, 25, 19, 19, 'question of words and names', 'Judicial Authority and Religious Questions', 'This connection highlights the theme of legal authority regarding religious matters. In both passages, the focus is on disputes related to religious beliefs and practices, with Paul being drawn into discussions about ''words and names'' and ''superstition.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 15, 54, 6, 4, 4, NULL, 'Questions and Strifes of Words', 'This connection highlights the theme of disputes over words and names in both passages. Acts 18:15 addresses the futility of such arguments, while 1 Timothy 6:4 warns against the pride and strife they can cause.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 15, 40, 27, 24, 24, 'look ye to it', 'Judgment and Innocence Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of evading judgment. Both passages emphasize the idea of individuals distancing themselves from responsibility, as seen in Pilate''s declaration of innocence and the refusal of the judge in Acts to intervene in matters of law.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 15, 54, 1, 4, 4, NULL, 'Questions and Edifying Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of avoiding disputes over trivial matters. Both passages emphasize the futility of engaging in questions that do not lead to godly edification.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 15, 55, 2, 23, 23, NULL, 'Avoiding Controversial Questions', 'Both passages emphasize the avoidance of disputes over trivial matters. Acts 18:15 suggests that questions of law and names should not be judged, while 2 Timothy 2:23 advises avoiding foolish questions that lead to strife.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 15, 56, 3, 9, 9, NULL, 'Avoiding Controversial Debates', 'Both passages emphasize the futility of engaging in disputes over the law and related matters. Acts 18:15 suggests that such questions should be handled by others, while Titus 3:9 advises avoiding them altogether as unprofitable.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 16, 19, 76, 10, 10, NULL, 'Wrath and Restraint Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of human wrath and its management. In Acts 18:16, the act of driving away reflects the restraint of conflict, while Psalms 76:10 speaks to the praise derived from human wrath and the divine ability to restrain it.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 16, 45, 13, 3, 4, 'drave them from the judgment seat', 'Authority and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the role of rulers as enforcers of justice. Both passages emphasize the authority of leaders to drive away evil and uphold good, reflecting their responsibility as ministers of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 16, 66, 12, 16, 16, 'drave them from the judgment seat', 'Judgment and Divine Intervention', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention in response to opposition. In Acts, the act of driving away reflects a judgment against adversaries, while in Revelation, the earth''s action symbolizes protection against the dragon''s flood.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 17, 46, 1, 1, 1, 'Sosthenes', 'Connection of Sosthenes in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the presence of Sosthenes in both passages. In Acts, he is mentioned as the chief ruler of the synagogue, while in 1 Corinthians, he is referred to as ''Sosthenes our brother.''', 'keyword', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 17, 30, 6, 6, 6, 'none of those things', 'Affliction and Indifference Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of indifference to suffering. In Acts, Gallio''s disregard for the beating of Sosthenes parallels the lack of grief for Joseph''s affliction in Amos.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 17, 44, 17, 32, 32, NULL, 'Response to Resurrection Message', 'Both passages emphasize the varied reactions to Paul''s preaching. In Acts 17:32, some mocked the resurrection, while in Acts 18:17, Sosthenes faces violence, reflecting the hostility towards the message of resurrection. This connection highlights the challenges faced by early Christians.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 17, 46, 1, 23, 23, 'the Greeks', 'Connection Between Greeks and Preaching', 'This connection highlights the response of the Greeks to the message of Christ. In Acts, the Greeks'' actions towards Sosthenes reflect their rejection of the Christian message, which is further emphasized in 1 Corinthians as they view Christ''s crucifixion as foolishness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 18, 44, 21, 24, 24, 'shorn his head', 'Connection of Vows and Purification', 'This connection highlights the practice of shaving heads as part of a vow or purification ritual. Both passages emphasize the significance of these actions in demonstrating adherence to Jewish customs.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 18, 4, 6, 18, 18, 'having shorn his head', 'Connection of Nazarite Vows', 'This connection highlights the act of shaving the head as a significant ritual in both passages. In Acts, Paul shaves his head after a vow, paralleling the Nazarite''s shaving in Numbers, which marks the completion of their separation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 18, 4, 6, 5, 9, 'having shorn his head', 'Connection of Vows in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the practice of taking a vow, as seen in both passages. In Acts 18:18, Paul shaves his head after fulfilling a vow, paralleling the instructions in Numbers 6:5 regarding the vow of separation and the shaving of the head.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 18, 44, 18, 2, 2, 'Priscilla and Aquila', 'Connection of Paul, Priscilla, and Aquila', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Paul, Priscilla, and Aquila. In Acts 18:2, Paul meets Aquila and Priscilla, while Acts 18:18 shows them traveling together, indicating their partnership in ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 18, 45, 16, 1, 1, 'Cenchrea', 'Connection through Cenchrea', 'This connection highlights the mention of Cenchrea in both passages. In Acts, Paul is noted to have been in Cenchrea, while Romans references Phebe as a servant of the church there.', 'keyword', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 18, 46, 9, 20, 20, 'having shorn his head in Cenchrea', 'Paul''s Adaptability to Culture', 'This connection highlights Paul''s willingness to adapt his behavior to different cultural contexts. In Acts, he takes a vow, indicating his commitment to Jewish customs, while in Corinthians, he expresses his strategy of becoming like the Jews to gain them.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 18, 48, 1, 21, 21, 'sailed thence into Syria', 'Paul''s Journey to Syria', 'This connection highlights Paul''s travels to Syria as noted in both passages. Acts 18:18 mentions Paul''s departure to Syria, while Galatians 1:21 references his arrival in the regions of Syria.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 19, 49, 1, 1, 1, 'Ephesus', 'Connection Between Ephesus References', 'This connection highlights Paul''s presence in Ephesus, where he engaged with the Jewish community. Both passages emphasize the significance of Ephesus in Paul''s ministry and his relationship with the believers there.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 19, 54, 1, 3, 3, 'Ephesus', 'Connection Between Ephesus References', 'Both passages emphasize Ephesus as a significant location for teaching and doctrine. Acts 18:19 mentions reasoning in the synagogue, while 1 Timothy 1:3 refers to instructing others in Ephesus about doctrine.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 19, 55, 1, 18, 18, 'Ephesus', 'Ministry in Ephesus', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Ephesus in Paul''s ministry. Acts 18:19 mentions his reasoning in the synagogue there, while 2 Timothy 1:18 refers to the ministering done in Ephesus.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 19, 44, 18, 4, 4, 'reasoned with the Jews', 'Reasoning in the Synagogue', 'Both passages emphasize the act of reasoning in the synagogue with Jews. This connection highlights Paul''s consistent engagement with Jewish audiences in Ephesus and elsewhere.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 19, 44, 18, 24, 24, 'Ephesus', 'Connection Through Ephesus', 'Both passages emphasize Ephesus as a significant location. In Acts 18:19, Paul arrives in Ephesus, and in Acts 18:24, Apollos comes to the same city, indicating its importance in early Christian ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 19, 46, 15, 32, 32, 'Ephesus', 'Ephesus Context Connection', 'This connection highlights the significance of Ephesus in both passages. In Acts, Paul engages with the Jews in the synagogue at Ephesus, while in 1 Corinthians, he references his struggles there, indicating a shared geographical and thematic context.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 19, 46, 16, 8, 8, 'Ephesus', 'Connection through Ephesus', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s presence in Ephesus. Acts 18:19 mentions his arrival and reasoning in the synagogue, while 1 Corinthians 16:8 indicates his intention to stay there until Pentecost.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 20, 41, 1, 37, 38, NULL, 'Mission and Movement', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of moving on to preach in new places. In Acts, the refusal to stay longer reflects a commitment to continue the mission, similar to Jesus'' decision to go to the next towns in Mark.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 20, 44, 20, 16, 16, 'tarry longer time with them', 'Paul''s Urgency in Travel', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s decision to not stay longer in one place. In Acts 18:20, he does not consent to tarry, while in Acts 20:16, he determines to sail quickly to reach Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 20, 44, 21, 13, 14, NULL, 'Paul''s Commitment to His Mission', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s determination to continue his mission despite the emotional pleas of others. In Acts 18:20, he chooses not to stay longer, while in Acts 21:13-14, he expresses his readiness to face suffering for the Lord''s name.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 20, 46, 16, 12, 12, 'desired him to tarry longer', 'Desire for Presence', 'Both passages emphasize a desire for someone''s presence, with Acts mentioning a desire for Paul to stay longer and 1 Corinthians expressing a desire for Apollos to visit. This connection highlights the theme of longing for fellowship among early Christian leaders.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 21, 46, 4, 19, 19, 'if God will', 'Paul''s Intent to Return', 'This connection highlights Paul''s intention to return to his audience in both passages. The phrase ''if the Lord will'' emphasizes his reliance on God''s will for his plans.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 21, 59, 4, 15, 15, 'if God will', 'Connection of Divine Will', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of God''s will in planning. Acts 18:21 expresses a commitment to return if it is God''s will, while James 4:15 advises to acknowledge the Lord''s will in future actions.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 21, 44, 20, 16, 16, 'keep this feast that cometh in Jerusalem', 'Paul''s Journey to Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize Paul''s urgency to reach Jerusalem for a significant feast. The mention of his desire to be in Jerusalem connects the two verses thematically around his travel plans.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 21, 45, 1, 10, 10, 'if God will', 'Journey and God''s Will', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of God''s will in the context of travel. Acts 18:21 mentions a journey to Jerusalem ''if God will,'' while Romans 1:10 expresses a desire for a prosperous journey ''by the will of God.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 21, 45, 15, 32, 32, 'if God will', 'Connection of God''s Will', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of the will of God in the Apostle Paul''s journey. In Acts, Paul expresses his intention to return if God wills, while in Romans, he seeks to come with joy by the will of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 21, 58, 6, 3, 3, 'if God will', 'Divine Will and Permission', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of divine permission in their plans. Acts 18:21 mentions ''if God will,'' while Hebrews 6:3 states ''if God permit,'' highlighting a shared theme of reliance on God''s will.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 21, 5, 16, 1, 1, 'keep this feast that cometh in Jerusalem', 'Connection of Feast Observance', 'This connection highlights the importance of observing feasts in both passages. Acts 18:21 mentions keeping a feast in Jerusalem, paralleling Deuteronomy 16:1''s command to keep the Passover.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 22, 44, 8, 40, 40, 'Cesarea', 'Connection Between Cesarea References', 'Both passages emphasize Cesarea as a significant location in the journeys of early Christians. Acts 18:22 mentions a journey to Cesarea, while Acts 8:40 highlights Philip''s preaching there, linking their missions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 22, 44, 10, 1, 1, 'Cesarea', 'Connection Between Cesarea and Cornelius', 'This connection highlights the significance of Cesarea as a location in both passages. Acts 18:22 mentions Cesarea, while Acts 10:1 introduces Cornelius, a notable figure from the same city.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 22, 44, 10, 24, 24, 'Cesarea', 'Connection through Cesarea', 'Both passages emphasize the location of Cesarea, highlighting its significance in the early church''s activities. Acts 18:22 mentions landing at Cesarea, while Acts 10:24 describes an event occurring there, linking the two narratives.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 22, 44, 11, 11, 11, 'Cesarea', 'Connection Between Cesarea Mentions', 'Both passages emphasize Cesarea as a significant location. In Acts 18:22, the mention of Cesarea connects to the earlier reference in Acts 11:11, highlighting its role in the early church''s activities.', 'keyword', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 22, 44, 11, 19, 27, 'went down to Antioch', 'Connection through Antioch', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Antioch as a center for early Christian teaching and community. Acts 11 describes the establishment of the church in Antioch, while Acts 18 mentions Paul''s visit to the church there.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 18, 22, 44, 13, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection Between Antioch and Church', 'This connection highlights the significance of Antioch as a central location for early Christian activity. Both passages emphasize the role of the church in Antioch, with Acts 13:1 introducing key figures and Acts 18:22 referencing the church as a destination.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
